<rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>智能新闻| smithsonianmag.com</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/rss/smart-news/</link><description>智能新闻的 RSS 提要</description><lastBuildDate>Wed, 01 Jul 2026 14:04:15 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>rfeed v1.1.1</generator><docs>https://github.com/svpino/rfeed/blob/master/README.md</docs><item><title>看看意大利花费数百万美元购买并在罗马公开展示的这些古代伊特鲁里亚壁画</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/see-these-ancient-etruscan-frescoes-that-italy-bought-for-millions-and-put-on-public-display-in-rome-180989046/</link><description>这些艺术品在墓室中发现，描绘了地中海世界古代英雄之间的战斗</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 20:52:03 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/see-these-ancient-etruscan-frescoes-that-italy-bought-for-millions-and-put-on-public-display-in-rome-180989046/</guid></item><item><title>这 17 张令人惊叹的草莓月亮照片展示了地球天然卫星的所有荣耀</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/these-17-stunning-photos-of-the-strawberry-moon-show-earths-natural-satellite-in-all-its-glory-180989050/</link><description>夏季的第一个满月在全球范围内呈现出令人眼花缭乱的视觉效果。从北半球的角度来看，它在天空中的位置较低，因此呈现出金色的色调</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 20:10:45 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/these-17-stunning-photos-of-the-strawberry-moon-show-earths-natural-satellite-in-all-its-glory-180989050/</guid></item><item><title>伦勃朗开始了一幅圣经绘画。另一位艺术家“相当粗糙”地完成了它。现在，修复工作揭示了失落已久的原作</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/rembrandt-began-a-biblical-painting-another-artist-finished-it-rather-crudely-now-restorations-have-revealed-the-long-lost-original-180989045/</link><description>2014 年，一位艺术品经销商在德国一家拍卖行偶然发现了《让小孩子来到我身边》。专家们现在已经小心地去除了这件被遗忘的杰作上的层层油漆。</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 19:10:41 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/rembrandt-began-a-biblical-painting-another-artist-finished-it-rather-crudely-now-restorations-have-revealed-the-long-lost-original-180989045/</guid></item><item><title>这只琥珀吊坠仅售出 5,588 英镑，原来是一幅罕见的都铎时代伊丽莎白一世肖像。现在，它将以 100,000 英镑的价格拍卖</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/sold-for-just-5588-this-amber-pendant-turned-out-to-be-a-rare-tudor-era-portrait-of-elizabeth-i-now-its-going-on-auction-for-100000-180989048/</link><description>一位工匠大师于 1600 年左右雕刻了这尊雕像，可能是受英国君主本人的委托。心形物体背面有一只鹦鹉，象征着伊丽莎白“童贞女王”的地位</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 17:19:18 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/sold-for-just-5588-this-amber-pendant-turned-out-to-be-a-rare-tudor-era-portrait-of-elizabeth-i-now-its-going-on-auction-for-100000-180989048/</guid></item><item><title>随着海洋变暖，大西洋中的“冷团”让科学家们感到困惑。这可能是关于当前关键系统的警告信号</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/as-the-ocean-warms-a-cold-blob-in-the-atlantic-has-puzzled-scientists-it-might-be-a-warning-sign-about-a-key-current-system-180988991/</link><description>自 1900 年以来，格陵兰岛和冰岛以南的一片水域已经冷却了近 1.8 华氏度。一项新的研究表明，这表明一个重要的洋流系统正在减弱，这可能会改变地球的气候</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 16:17:17 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/as-the-ocean-warms-a-cold-blob-in-the-atlantic-has-puzzled-scientists-it-might-be-a-warning-sign-about-a-key-current-system-180988991/</guid></item><item><title>尼安德特人为何灭绝？一项研究表明，近亲繁殖可能不是西北欧动物灭绝的罪魁祸首</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/why-did-neanderthals-go-extinct-inbreeding-probably-wasnt-to-blame-for-their-demise-in-northwestern-europe-a-study-suggests-180989032/</link><description>与居住在西伯利亚的尼安德特人相比，在该物种消失前不久居住在现在的比利时和法国的尼安德特人似乎基因多样化且健康</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/why-did-neanderthals-go-extinct-inbreeding-probably-wasnt-to-blame-for-their-demise-in-northwestern-europe-a-study-suggests-180989032/</guid></item><item><title>火星漫游者在这颗红色星球上发现了复杂的碳，标志着又一次探测到了生命的组成部分</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/mars-rover-spots-complex-carbon-on-the-red-planet-marking-yet-another-detection-of-a-building-block-of-life-180989043/</link><description>与最近的其他发现一起，毅力号的新发现证实了火星曾经拥有可以支持生物生存的条件，但这并不是古代生物体存在的明确迹象</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 13:38:51 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/mars-rover-spots-complex-carbon-on-the-red-planet-marking-yet-another-detection-of-a-building-block-of-life-180989043/</guid></item><item><title>梵蒂冈教皇居住的拉斐尔壁画大厅正在激光的帮助下进行急需的修复</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-vaticans-hall-of-raphael-frescoes-in-the-popes-residence-is-getting-a-much-needed-restoration-with-the-help-of-lasers-180989041/</link><description>文物保护人员将在接下来的五年内清理和修饰文艺复兴时期的壁画，这些壁画的历史可以追溯到 16 世纪初</description><pubDate>Tue, 30 Jun 2026 13:31:51 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-vaticans-hall-of-raphael-frescoes-in-the-popes-residence-is-getting-a-much-needed-restoration-with-the-help-of-lasers-180989041/</guid></item><item><title>创始人宣布独立后，印刷商迅速为讲德语的美国人翻译文本</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/after-the-founders-declared-independence-printers-quickly-translated-the-text-for-german-speaking-americans-180989039/</link><description>该文件以哥特式字体印刷，在费城翻译。现存的两本副本之一将在美国 250 岁生日之前在柏林展出</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 22:19:22 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/after-the-founders-declared-independence-printers-quickly-translated-the-text-for-german-speaking-americans-180989039/</guid></item><item><title>来自南极洲的化石在抽屉里放了 40 年。事实证明，这是非洲大陆发现的第一块恐龙骨头</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-fossil-from-antarctica-sat-in-a-drawer-for-40-years-it-turned-out-to-be-the-first-dinosaur-bone-ever-found-on-the-continent-180989042/</link><description>在被遗忘了几十年之后，神秘的尾椎终于被确定为泰坦龙的一部分。这一发现有助于研究人员了解恐龙可能如何穿越地球最南端的地区</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 20:40:09 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-fossil-from-antarctica-sat-in-a-drawer-for-40-years-it-turned-out-to-be-the-first-dinosaur-bone-ever-found-on-the-continent-180989042/</guid></item><item><title>成吉思汗因其广阔的帝国和可怕的战士而被人们铭记。这次展览探讨了他的文化遗产</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/genghis-khan-is-remembered-for-his-vast-empire-and-fearsome-warriors-this-exhibition-explores-his-cultural-legacy-180989040/</link><description>皇家军械博物馆将展出近 250 件稀有文物（从马鞍到早期纸币），揭示蒙古帝国经常被忽视的一面</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 20:19:27 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/genghis-khan-is-remembered-for-his-vast-empire-and-fearsome-warriors-this-exhibition-explores-his-cultural-legacy-180989040/</guid></item><item><title>人类和类人猿以相似的节奏和时机咯咯笑，这表明我们在 1500 万年前就分享了我们的笑声风格</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/humans-and-great-apes-giggle-with-a-similar-rhythm-and-timing-suggesting-we-have-shared-our-style-of-laughter-for-15-million-years-180989031/</link><description>了解笑声如何进化可以揭示人类语言的秘密</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 18:30:01 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/humans-and-great-apes-giggle-with-a-similar-rhythm-and-timing-suggesting-we-have-shared-our-style-of-laughter-for-15-million-years-180989031/</guid></item><item><title>科学家们加倍确定地球上最古老的撞击坑的年龄，再次测算它的年龄超过三十亿年</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/scientists-double-down-on-age-of-earths-oldest-meteorite-impact-crater-dating-it-again-at-more-than-three-billion-years-old-180989023/</link><description>去年，地质学家测算西澳大利亚陨石坑的年龄为 34.7 亿年，但其他专家对此提出了争议。现在，他们将这一估计修正为 30.2 亿年——但有些人仍然不相信</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 17:16:50 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/scientists-double-down-on-age-of-earths-oldest-meteorite-impact-crater-dating-it-again-at-more-than-three-billion-years-old-180989023/</guid></item><item><title>研究人员在科学上首次发现了人类在岩石艺术和洞穴墙壁上留下的古代 DNA</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-a-scientific-first-researchers-recovered-ancient-dna-that-humans-left-behind-on-rock-art-and-cave-walls-180989038/</link><description>洞穴壁上的 DNA 保存情况变化很大，但科学家表示，他们的工作是深入了解我们富有创造力的祖先的重要一步</description><pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2026 14:27:58 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-a-scientific-first-researchers-recovered-ancient-dna-that-humans-left-behind-on-rock-art-and-cave-walls-180989038/</guid></item><item><title>在墨西哥丛林深处，考古学家发现了一座失落的玛雅城市，可能会提供有关文明崩溃前夕的线索</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/deep-in-the-mexican-jungle-archaeologists-discovered-a-lost-maya-city-that-may-yield-clues-about-the-civilization-just-before-it-collapsed-180989030/</link><description>研究人员砍伐了超过三英里的植被才能到达该地点，该地点位于熟悉的伐木路径范围之外。在那里，他们发现了独特的雕刻石碑和祭坛</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 21:44:58 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/deep-in-the-mexican-jungle-archaeologists-discovered-a-lost-maya-city-that-may-yield-clues-about-the-civilization-just-before-it-collapsed-180989030/</guid></item><item><title>观看有史以来在可见光下拍摄的最详细的银河系心脏照片，这将有助于天文学家寻找系外行星</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/see-the-most-detailed-photo-of-the-milky-ways-heart-ever-taken-in-visible-light-which-will-help-astronomers-hunt-for-exoplanets-180989027/</link><description>欧洲航天局的欧几里得望远镜是为了研究暗物质和暗能量而建造的，但去年的一天，它捕捉到了照亮我们银河系中心的密集恒星</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 21:09:42 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/see-the-most-detailed-photo-of-the-milky-ways-heart-ever-taken-in-visible-light-which-will-help-astronomers-hunt-for-exoplanets-180989027/</guid></item><item><title>历经多年打造，国家地理探索博物馆将带您踏上冒险之旅</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/years-in-the-making-national-geographics-museum-of-exploration-is-here-to-take-you-on-an-adventure-180989034/</link><description>翻新后的空间凸显了这个拥有 138 年历史的标志性品牌的标志，从野生动物摄影到人类学研究</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 20:03:24 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/years-in-the-making-national-geographics-museum-of-exploration-is-here-to-take-you-on-an-adventure-180989034/</guid></item><item><title>科学家破译了一部因维苏威火山喷发而冻结的 2000 年前哲学论文的残片</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/scientists-have-deciphered-the-surviving-fragments-of-a-2000-year-old-philosophical-treatise-frozen-in-time-by-mount-vesuvius-eruption-180989036/</link><description>这份纸莎草手稿是由火山灰保存下来的庞大图书馆的一部分。现在，剩余的段落——审视伦理、知识和人性——自公元 79 年以来首次可供访问</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 19:51:06 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/scientists-have-deciphered-the-surviving-fragments-of-a-2000-year-old-philosophical-treatise-frozen-in-time-by-mount-vesuvius-eruption-180989036/</guid></item><item><title>艺术太热？由于欧洲创纪录的热浪，巴黎一些博物馆和地标关闭或缩短开放时间</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/too-hot-for-art-some-paris-museums-and-landmarks-close-or-reduce-hours-amid-a-record-heat-wave-in-europe-180989029/</link><description>与此同时，其他机构也提供空调空间，为居民和游客提供避暑的方式</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 19:46:30 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/too-hot-for-art-some-paris-museums-and-landmarks-close-or-reduce-hours-amid-a-record-heat-wave-in-europe-180989029/</guid></item><item><title>诺曼·洛克威尔 (Norman Rockwell) 在白宫展出了数十年的彩色画作中捕捉到了西翼的喧嚣。他们现在首次出现在公众视野中</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/norman-rockwell-captured-the-hustle-of-the-west-wing-in-colorful-drawings-displayed-for-decades-in-the-white-house-theyre-now-on-public-view-for-the-first-time-180989025/</link><description>这些作品是为了在第二次世界大战最激烈的时期使富兰克林·罗斯福总统变得人性化而委托创作的</description><pubDate>Fri, 26 Jun 2026 18:40:32 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/norman-rockwell-captured-the-hustle-of-the-west-wing-in-colorful-drawings-displayed-for-decades-in-the-white-house-theyre-now-on-public-view-for-the-first-time-180989025/</guid></item></channel></rss>